<module>
  <title>demonyms</title>
  <p>Demonyms are adjectives and <a href="?xx=nouns/common_nouns">common nouns</a> which have been derived from <a href="?xx=nouns/toponymic_proper_nouns">toponymic proper nouns</a>, and describe a person (or
    other entity) originating from, or otherwise associated with the place identified by the proper noun.</p>
  <p>Demonyms are typically formed by adding the suffix <m>-(e)ach</m> to the place name root, e.g.</p> 
  <ul>
    <li><i>Leòdhas</i> <en>Lewis</en> ⇒ <m>Leòdhas<u>ach</u></m> <en>(person) from Lewis</en></li>
    <li><i>Muile</i> <en>Mull</en> ⇒ <m>Muile<u>ach</u></m> <en>(person) from Mull</en></li>
  </ul>
  <p>Sometimes the root is simplified somewhat, e.g. <i>Moireibh</i> <en>Moray</en> ⇒ <m>Moire<u>ach</u></m> <en>(person) from Moray</en>.</p>
  <hr/>
  <p>When used as an <u>adjective</u>, a demonym declines in the usual way, e.g. <i>fear Muileach</i>
    <en>Mull man</en>, <i>bean Mhuileach</i>
    <en>Mull woman</en>
    <boxlink ref="#adjective_declension"/>.</p>
  <box id="adjective_declension">
    <title>declension of denonymic adjectives</title>
    <p>Denonymic adjectives in <m>-(e)ach</m> decline just like any other adjective –</p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <td/>
          <th>feminine</th>
          <th>masculine</th>
          <th>broad plural</th>
          <th>slender plural</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <th>nominative</th>
          <td>(caileag) <m>M<u>h</u>uileach</m></td>
          <td>(balach) <m>Muileach</m></td>
          <td>(caileagan) <m>Muileach</m></td>
          <td>(balaich) <m>M<u>h</u>uileach</m></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>dative</th>
          <td>(le caileig) <m>M<u>h</u>uil<u>i</u>ch</m></td>
          <td>(le balach) <m>Muileach</m></td>
          <td>(le caileagan) <m>Muileach</m></td>
          <td>(le balaich) <m>M<u>h</u>uileach</m></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>genitive</th>
          <td>(taigh caileige) <m>Muil<u>i</u>ch<u>e</u></m></td>
          <td>(taigh balaich) <m>M<u>h</u>uil<u>i</u>ch</m></td>
          <td>(taigh chaileagan) <m>Muileach</m></td>
          <td>(taigh bhalach) <m>Muileach</m></td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </box>
  <p>When used as a (masculine) <u>noun</u>, a demonym slenderises in the genitive singular and in the (non-genitive) plural, 
    e.g. <i>Muileach</i> <en>Mull man</en>, <i>Muilich</i> <en>Mull men</en>, <i>bean Muilich</i> <en>a Mull man’s wife</en> 
    <boxlink ref="#noun_declension"/>.</p>
  <box id="noun_declension">
    <title>declension of denonymic nouns</title>
    <p>Denonymic masculine nouns in <m>-(e)ach</m> decline just like any other regular masculine noun, 
      slenderising in the genitive singular and in the non-genitive plural –</p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <td/>
          <th>singular</th>
          <th>plural</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <th>nominative</th>
          <td><m>Muileach</m></td>
          <td><m>Muil<u>i</u>ch</m></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>dative</th>
          <td>(le) <m>Muileach</m></td>
          <td>(le) <m>Muil<u>i</u>ch</m></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>genitive</th>
          <td>(taigh) <m>Muil<u>i</u>ch</m></td>
          <td>(taigh) <m>M<u>h</u>uileach</m></td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </box>
  <p>The ‘femaleness’ of women described with a demonymic noun can be brought into focus with the traditional prefix <strong><a href="?gd=bana">ban(a)-</a></strong>, 
    e.g. <m>ban-Albannach</m> <en>Scotswoman</en>, <m>bana-Hearach</m> <en>Harris woman</en>.</p>
